  "local_port": 44094,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I set a default font in Gmail?",
  "response": "As of my knowledge cutoff in October 2023, Gmail doesn't allow you to set a default font for all your emails directly. However, you can change the font for individual emails while composing them. Here\u2019s how you can do it:\n\n### Changing the Font in Composed Emails:\n1. **Open Gmail** and click **Compose** to start a new email.\n2. In the compose window, you\u2019ll see a toolbar with formatting options (e.g., font type, size, bold, italic, etc.).\n3. Click the **font dropdown menu** (usually displays \"Sans Serif\" by default).\n4. Select the font you want to use for that specific email.\n\n### Workaround to \"Set\" a Default Font:\nIf you want to use a specific font consistently, you can:\n1. Compose a new email.\n2. Change the font to your preferred choice.\n3. Use this email as a **template**: Instead of sending it, save it as a draft and copy its content whenever you need to write a new email.\n\n### Using Templates (for Gmail Accounts with Templates Enabled):\n1. Enable **Templates** in Gmail (if not already enabled):\n   - Go to **Settings** (gear icon) > **See all settings** > **Advanced**.\n   - Enable **Templates** and save changes.\n2. Compose a new email with your preferred font.\n3. After setting up the email, click the **three-dot menu** in the compose window > **Templates** > **Save draft as template** > **Save as new template**.\n4. Use this template whenever you need to compose an email with your preferred font.\n\nUnfortunately, Gmail does not currently offer a native way to set a default font globally for all emails. If this feature becomes available in the future, you may need to check Gmail\u2019s settings or updates for new options.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
